<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> TTT: Combining Culture/ Free Peoples<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 29, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
     I&#8217;ve already covered the three minion cultures of the Two Towers. Now it&#8217;s time to look at the possibilities of the free peoples side. I will try to cover all the cultures in one article, so this will be the last article in the series. I promise.<br />
<br />
<br />
First, I&#8217;d like to start this article off with by far the most underused culture, the Dwarves. Now more than likely when the Two Towers released, you weren&#8217;t terribly exited about the new Dwarf cards that were to be released with the set, but they are definitely worth a second look. The new Dwarven culture appears to be centered around stacking cards. This seems to be a favorable alternative to drawing random cards. Ever My Heart Rises gives you 6 cards stacked and lets you pick and choose the cards you need for your hand. This can be key to either your fellowship or your shadow side. Essentially, the old dwarf deck played with Moria, drew cards, and set up a huge minion hand for a swarm. This can do basically the same thing except it is much more reliable. This also helps get the cards you need faster to get your fellowship running. Courtesy of My Hall is a strangely useful card when used right. It grabs a card from the discard pile. You can put it back to heal one of your dwarves OR keep it until&#8230;oh&#8230;a Dwarven Foresight makes its way into your hand, then take it. With 2 cards, you can take your pick from the discard. Not bad. Alright, here&#8217;s another surefire way to set up a healing engine for your dwarves. You know that old card Dwarven Heart no one ever used. Use it. Play it to heal off 2 or so wounds, then use Axe of Erebor, Restless Axe, or best of all, Rest By Blind Night to shuffle it back and the process starts all over again. That way you take in the advantages of Dwarven Heart, but it won&#8217;t stick around long enough to deal you the disadvantages.<br />
Unfortunately, there are no new dwarf companions in the new set save for two versions of Gimli, neither of which is useful in a dwarf deck, thus you&#8217;ll have to stick to Gimli, Gloin, Farin, and Fror. You can still make it work, though. If the number of minions gets to be trouble, try this. Disquiet of Our People + From the Armory let&#8217;s you get rid of an extra card from your hand and allows your dwarf to fight 2 minions without dying as long as he&#8217;s not overwhelmed. Then play Dwarven heart to heal the wounds off and a condition shuffler or discarder to get it off. Or try Come Here Lad with Courtesy of My Hall to heal the dwarves you want when you need them healed. Possession discard a newfound problem? Beneath the Mountain is your solution and besides, it gives Gloin a +1 strength so why not? Wanting those events back? Grimrir and Great Works Begun There&#8230;and let&#8217;s not forget our old friend Thrarin. Throw in Filbert and you&#8217;re in good shape. <br />
<br />
<br />
Now you&#8217;re probably wondering why I haven&#8217;t mentioned culture combines yet. Well, there are a many. The only combining that seems to be apparent is using him with Legolas. These two work VERY well together in the new set. If you&#8217;re playing with unbound hobbits and Lockbearer with Merry and Pippin, My Axe Is Notched and Final Count, with 3 tokens on each he&#8217;s a whopping strength of 11. Give him his Axe and a Hand Axe and he is a strength of 14! Discard with the Axe of Erebor and add a Dwarven Bracers and&#8230;well, you get the picture. Then you have Legolas as well who&#8217;s kicking some tail as well. The common versions of these companions are a great start when you haven&#8217;t got a better start. <br />
<br />
Now let&#8217;s take a look at the elves. Ah yes, look at all the elves that come into this set that shouldn&#8217;t even be there. Sorry, but am I the only one bothered by the fact that the elves are blown out of proportion in the movie when they are not even there in the original story? Oh, well. For the purposes of the card game, though, this is a good thing. Say goodbye to the Lorien Elf because the big guns are here. Finally, elves are useful for something other than archery. In fact, they&#8217;ve practically done away with elf archery in this set. Now those elven bows give strength bonuses, damage bonuses, and reduce minion strength instead of helping to accumulate archery points. This can be a good or bad thing. Unfortunately you can&#8217;t use all the best elves, arm them all with bows, sit back and watch their minions die before they get to fight. However, these elves are already well rounded at 6 strength and by adding an bow and an elven sword, they reach strength 9, which is not half bad. Keep in mind as well that they can make the difference between minion and elf strength greater by discarding. Their new condition discard is very effective as it can be used from the very start of the game. <br />
<br />
Some cards like the Lorien Swordsman, similar to the Rohan culture, operate off wounds. The Swordsman has similar game text to rare Eomer&#8217;s, making him effective in combination with a mount. You would have to use the more expensive mount and you would have to get a Rohan man out, but it might be worth a try. Notice that cards like Killing Field, Lorien is Most Welcome, and Blades Drawn also effectively use wounds to your advantage. The first 2 can tear Uruk-hai to bits and pieces and are not too Nazgul friendly either. Well, if both cultures work well off wounds, then why not try them together. It could work. Get 3 elves out. Allies, companions, whatever. Stick Eomer and Firefoot in there. Alright, now you can assign 2 minions to him, potentially prevent both of them from being fierce and completely nullifying the damage bonuses&#8230;or if you&#8217;re using Blades drawn give Eomer +4 strength. Not a bad thing, right? Let&#8217;s also not forget our friend Greenleaf. With a simple exertion, he can stop a brutal fierce skirmish, nullify a damage bonus or simply make a minion strength -2 or a combination of any of these. You can just keep on pelting them this way with unaimed archery as well. These conditions really increase possibilities for the elves. Unfortunately, it only lasts one turn. Bummer, but it is still useful. However, once you have sufficiently wounded those minions, you need only use Calaglin and Lorien Guardian to take out the remaining wounds, Dinendal to take extra twilight away and, suddenly, a double move becomes the favorable option. Elves also have a way to play competitively against almost any deck. For swarm, there&#8217;s archery. For high strength powerhouses, the exerting and wounding deal works well and you&#8217;ve got high strength elves to back you up. Conditions? Elven has arguably the two best condition discards in the game. If site control becomes a problem, you&#8217;ve got Haldir and cards like Sword Wall and Night Without End which have a subtle alternate text which can be useful as well when you aren&#8217;t playing against site control&#8230;plus if they aren&#8217;t Haldir is strength of 7. Elves even have drawing capabilities with Alliance Reforged. The Legolas&#8217;s from this set are both not elf oriented. The rare Legolas is the cornerstone of an unbound hobbit strategy while common Legolas works quite well with friend Gimli and doesn&#8217;t do too badly for Trust Me either. There are quite a few new possibilities for the elves, so for those of you who love the blue cards, here is your chance. <br />
<br />
<br />
Now we reach Gandalf&#8217;s culture. One of the biggest new cards from the set is Treebeard the Ent. At a strength of 12 and 2 home sites, and a fairly good game text for just 4 twilight isn&#8217;t bad. You don&#8217;t even have to spot Gandalf to play him. The rare Treebeard in particular is a must for the unbound hobbit strategy. Discard them, stack them, then play them again to get bonuses from Dauntless Hunter and Lockbearer. The common versions have text which lets you discard them in a skirmish, but allows the shadow player to counter it. The rare versions only get rid of one minion of a particular culture, but does not allow the shadow player to retaliate. Personally, my choice would be rare Pippin and common Merry. The rare Gandalf from the set greatly aids the unbound hobbit strategy. While Treebeard only adds 1 to get the hobbits back in play, Gandalf does not require an exertion. Treebeard is an ally. Gandalf is a companion. Treebeard only can save the unbound hobbits while Gandalf can get back any character. Companion or ally for 2 extra twilight. While the common Gandalf is completely oriented towards getting twilight through to skirmish as is his new Staff. The only problem with that strategy is you have to use expensive Gandalf spells and that will almost eliminate the possibility of a second move. In addition, minions like the Southrons can use that twilight after the shadow phase, thus denying you the advantages and hurting you at the same time. This makes the Gandalf strategy very risky. However, if your shadow is strong, it might work. This opens new strategies for old cards like Deep In Thought and even Unknown Perils. The downside is that your fellowship is not likely to win the race to site 9. One way you can make up for the disadvantage of a slow fellowship is to use shadow to equalize it. In other words, put in cards that reduce the move limit for your opponent. Playing Isengard? Remember burden adding for this culture? Traitor&#8217;s Voice is one way to take advantage of those burdens. Provided you are in a two player game and your opponent can&#8217;t increase the limit, they will traveling no faster than yourself. Unlike your opponent, though, you actually have the option of moving again if you feel daring enough. <br />
<br />
Think about the possibility of Gandalf in a Rohan deck. Crazy? Maybe, but not with Shadowfax. He becomes just as good if not better than the rest of them. In addition, it allows you to play the Hearken to Me card which makes Theoden, in combination with his sword, a formidable fighting companion immune to shadow conditions. Gandalf Greyhame can be particularly useful as he can play back discarded allies. This means if villagers die because their home site is under shadow control, you can wait until you liberate it, then play them back. One of the best ways to use Greyhame is to discard companions early in the game to avoid large fellowship, then play them back when you get closer to site 9, where the benefits start outweighing the disadvantages. Let Ranger of the North sit in your discard pile, then play him out before the home stretch to site 9 and you&#8217;ve got the ability to take on four minions, which is key when you are moving to the end. Now back to the unbound hobbits. As it ends up, rare Gandalf fits in rather nicely with the self-discarding hobbits. If we&#8217;re using Gandalf, why not use Wielder of the Flame to give one of your unbound hobbit friends the ability to take an extra minion with him before he discards himself or better yet, stealth out of it with Escape or one of the new stealth events, then take 2 more fierce minions, then discard. You&#8217;ve taken care of 4 skirmishes with one of the weakest companions in the game and they aren&#8217;t even gone for good. This works best with little or no twilight as the shadow player can retaliate by removing so much twilight. While the best strategy is to have no twilight, if they do remove it, they will have less or no twilight to prevent you from discarding Merry or Pippin. There are many other cards to take advantage of here, but I will stop there.<br />
<br />
<br />
I&#8217;ll cover the Shire next. I think I&#8217;ve covered the unbound hobbits sufficiently, so let&#8217;s look at the Ring-bound ones. Frodo and Sam. Since every deck has Frodo, it&#8217;s probably important to see the advantages he has, right? Frodo&#8217;s Cloak is like a mobile hobbit stealth that can be used through site 4. If you&#8217;re past that, you remove a burden and heal Frodo. Both of these abilities are quite useful, so it can&#8217;t hurt to throw it in. The main strategy with Ring-bound hobbits are adding burdens for advantages, then removing them. This brings back usefulness to one of my old favorites, The Shire Countryside. I know what you&#8217;re thinking. It is a shame you can&#8217;t use Tired Traveler to heal companions by playing them, but that would be cheap anyway. Brace of Coneys is one way. A simple card you can play down, then discard when you have three Countrysides. Not only does it remove a burden, but heals three wounds as well. While hobbits are not known to win skirmishes, if you can find inventive ways to do this, Good Work would help. Discard condition. Remove 3 burdens. Heal 3 wounds or 6 wounds with 2 Countrysides, or 9 wounds with 3. The catch is you need burdens. That is not a problem with the new set. There are all kinds of fabulous cards that add burdens. From healing your Ring-bound companion twice to playing the next 2 sites to wounding minions the hobbits are skirmishing. to discarding conditions. Let&#8217;s also not forget PATHS. Just make sure that your burden adding frenzy doesn&#8217;t get your count too high.<br />
<br />
<br />
Rohan, of all the cultures, minion or free peoples, is in my opinion, the most impressive. It is well thought out and gives rise to many different deck types. This culture seems to be greatly possession influenced. The obvious deck branching from this culture is an all Rohan deck. This would probably include Eomer and either Elite Rider and Eowyn as your start or maybe even Theoden, then a few other companions in there. In my opinion, though, don&#8217;t use Elite Rider if you don&#8217;t start him. Too expensive. If you don&#8217;t start Theoden, though, keep in mind that you can still get him out with the Throne Room. I will mention more on Theoden a little later in this section, but for now let&#8217;s look at other cards. One more obvious advantage to Rohan is their mounts. Use mounts to exert minions and get bonuses from it, then win skirmishes with all sorts of different abilities and weapons. Other than the mounts, though, what cards make Rohan different than other cultures? Well, what about Weapon Store? Until now, being able to get back weapons dropped by the notorious Cantea or some other evil method. Now it&#8217;s quite easy. What&#8217;s more is that it is even more important with the new set. This culture also happens to be the biggest weakness to Rohan. The Dunland culture. Possession discard is the worse way to screw up a Rohan deck. No more mounts, no more spears, no more winning&#8230;but wait, there&#8217;s still hope. Weapon Store is its name. Unfortunately, that solves only half the problem and it doesn&#8217;t get mounts back. The other half of the problem is the Dunland men&#8217;s low vitality. It&#8217;s a problem because they can&#8217;t exert and, thus, you cannot get much needed bonuses. Since Dunland men have generally high strength, it is difficult to win without possessions. In a way, though, losing mounts against Dunland is no big loss, because, obviously, they would not be of much use. True, you don&#8217;t get damage bonuses, but that hardly matters against Dunland. Now Weapon Store is a card you might just put in a non-Rohan deck. The ability to get Hand Weapons back is not useful only to Dunland, so why not throw in a Rohan companion or ally that you can continually heal and be able to cycle the toys back. Another very useful card limited to Rohan alone is Simbelmyne. The ability to grab any Rohan companion, ally, or possession from your draw deck is huge. In a Rohan deck, this is almost like being able to take the card of choice. In addition, Rohan introduces 3 new mains.<br />
<br />
Eomer, particularly, the rare version, being the most powerful of the Rohan companions is sure to show up as a starting companion in any such deck as he plays for a measly 2 twilight when another Rohan man is out. This allows him to start with any other Rohan companion in the game. When this guy is pumped up, he rivals Aragorn. Give him his spear and Firefoot and he&#8217;s a base strength of 9 and that number goes up by an increment of 2 for each wound. Since Firefoot allows 2 minions to skirmish him, both must exert making Eomer a strength of 13 instead. His spear, in combination with his mount, will guarantee that no minion he is victorious over will survive the fight. Why not give him a Flaming Brand, too. Now he&#8217;s 14. Not bad. That&#8217;s enough to beat most minions. Although he is meant to be in Rohan decks, Eomer still fits in quite nicely in other deck types as well. Archery for instance. If a minion doesn&#8217;t die from archery, he will when Eomer gets through with him. In fact, any deck that works off wounded minions will benefit from Eomer. Common Eomer can be useful as well. Healing a Rohan ally and be the equivalent of an extra archery or a wound of a Rohan companion or a needed strength bonus. I, however, still recommend using the rare version as healing villagers, who are most of the Rohan allies can be achieved through Well Stored. <br />
<br />
Eowyn, unlike her brother, is not at powerful, but more versatile in different decks. The common version her who I like to call the &#8216;Enquea disappointer&#8217; relate to keeping other companions alive while the &#8216;just die, already&#8217; Eowyn or the rare version relates to keeping herself alive. It&#8217;s really just a matter of choice. If you have reliable ways of keeping the rest of your companions alive, maybe you should try the rare version. If, however, you are constantly losing your key companions, perhaps, you should consider the common version. <br />
<br />
Theoden is, by far, the weakest of the three. By himself, even no names like Ceorl make him look bad. His game text is ok, but not terrific. The common version can keep site control under control provided you have a way to heal him or give him more vitality. His sword, Herrugrim, gives him 2 strength, a vitality and damage +1. I&#8217;ve already mentioned the Gandalf Condition.  With both of these, he&#8217;s a decent strength of 10 and vitality of 4. That&#8217;s at least 3 sites you can liberate. Not bad. I get the feeling that he may find his way into non Rohan decks that lack site liberation. Now the premium version. Fortunately, he doesn&#8217;t rely on exertions as he is deficient in that area. Instead he focuses on healing your fellowship party. While it is limited to once per turn, it can certainly be helpful. Being able to heal always helps and he doesn&#8217;t need to be souped up either, though it does help. <br />
<br />
I particularly like Fortress Never Fallen. It&#8217;s that extra mile that makes Rohan even better. Condition discard. Did I also forget to mention that Rohan men can bear Armor as well. This only increases their potency. If you happen to slip in Rohan with Gondor or Gondor with Rohan, then Help in Doubt and Need may be the missing link to a good deck. Using Valleys of the Mark? Maybe some Ring-bound Rangers and Ranger Bows might be what you need. Don&#8217;t forget what I said about Rohan and elves either. <br />
<br />
<br />
Lastly, is what I believe to be the most potent deck type. Ring-bound men, when equipped properly, can beat almost any deck type. As you can see, they are work off roaming minions, but they are actually built similar to the Rohan culture. Rare Faramir is the Ring-bound equivalent to Eomer, Ranger of Ithilien is the equivalent to Elite Rider and so on. Ring-bound men, though, unlike Rohan, are weak to no culture.  Nazgul can be dealt with by including Flaming Brands and other similar tools. Men and anything else roaming become fodder to Ranger Bows. In fact, if you can keep minions roaming long enough, this can be like using aimed archery. Mablung, for instance, with a Ranger Bow can take out any roaming minion with two exertions. The same goes for Damrod and any man opposing him. Faramir&#8217;s Bow is the same except he gets one extra wound out of his. As for dealing with Orcs and Uruk-hai. There&#8217;s a special surprise for them. Ithilien Trap. Now, this card is generally efficient in any Ring-bound man related deck. However, when used with the rare Ring from the new set, Orc Bane becomes much more potent. This and Ithilien Trap can potentially eliminate all minion during the maneuver phase. This means no archery, no skirmish, no nothing. If this doesn&#8217;t get the job done, your Ranger Bows certainly will. If you don&#8217;t like Orc Bane, but like the idea of maneuver elimination, try Defend it and Hope which is also useful against Uruk-hai. With 3 Gondorian Rangers, you can keep every minion type roaming the entire game, so, with that said, Curse them and Arrows Thick In the Air are nice as well. Not to mention, Armor also helps you combat the Uruk-hai as well. Since Orc tend to deal wounds with archery much of the time, you can eliminate them via Orc Bane, Arrows Thick, or whatever else you can think of. They also tend to deal wounds. At least, the Sauron do. Sam&#8217;s Pack can heal one of your Ring-bound companions a turn and let&#8217;s not forget Athelas. Burden adding can be be dealt with efficiently by simply using Tired Traveler. Almost shuts it down right there.<br />
<br />
Let&#8217;s not forget some of those great realms cards that even greater now. For instance, Swordsman of the Northern Kingdom will give +4 strength most of the time, now. Shards of Narsil can hold most of your deck&#8230;and, at last, you can discard those Gondor Bowmens without having to exert key companions. Gondor was strong in the last set, but it only gets stronger with this set. For the first time ever, you can now have 4 copies of No Stranger on the table at once. Light Shining Faintly will keep your fellowship members fully healed and Tired Traveler will take the burden away when you play another companion. In fact, this common Frodo additionally allows you to start more burdens than normal. Well, I could very well be wrong, but I see no deck types that Ring-bound men cannot effectively beat. Ah, yes. I forgot swarm. If Orc Bane doesn&#8217;t deliver, then you can always count on Banner of the White Tree and Elendil&#8217;s Valor. <br />
<br />
Well, that&#8217;s it. I&#8217;ve covered every culture from the set. I know this may have been a bit long and I thank you for reading it all the way to the end and I hope it was worth it. I hope that these article encourage innovative decks and game play&#8230;because I always like to see new strategies being used and I am always looking for cool ways to use old and new cards. <br />
<br />
